<HL>
   NASA Can Hardly Wait to Read
   Next Month's Letters to the Editor
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Earth to Owen Lipstein]
   With Earth Day media hype reaching incredible heights, Mr.
Lipstein, owner of Mother Earth News, wants to do the same --
by taking his magazine into the heavens. On Sunday, Earth Day
that is, a recorded version of the magazine will be beamed
into outer space via a satellite transmission from Mount
Everest. A team of climbers will broadcast it from
battery-powered equipment at Everest Base Camp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The sonic message in a bottle is taken from the
March/April issue of Mother Earth News. It contains many
heartfelt messages contributed by the famous and not-so
famous about the world's environment and its present
condition. Alfred Meyer, Mother Earth's editor in chief,
asked an assortment of people to send in messages they would
want blasted into space, supposedly to be received by someone
or something.
   Ann Landers, usually a hopeful sort, was gloomy in her
reading: "Our planet is dying," she lamented. Pope John Paul
II spoke of a "cosmos endowed with its own integrity, its own
internal, dynamic balance." Gonzo journalist Hunter S.
Thompson was simply gonzo: "Yesterday's weirdness is
tomorrow's reason why." Michael Kramer, a third grader in
Stamford, Conn., was more clear thinking: "The rain forest
has plants and animals found nowhere else in the world. . . .
It also helps us breathe."
   Not everyone was so willing to participate. One respected
(but apparently xenophobic) scientist refused the invitation
to send a message. "He said he didn't want to advertise our
presence. Whatever is out there might be hostile," Mr. Meyer
says.
   Cynics might consider this a mere gimmick by a troubled
publisher to grab some cheap publicity. Mr. Lipstein recently
ran into a cash squeeze, with the result that he wasn't
mailing his magazines to subscribers on time. He eventually
had to sell his American Health magazine.
   "It's promotional," Mr. Lipstein concedes, "but it's also
a profound thought." He certainly knows a good thing when he
sees it. The resurging interest in saving the Earth is
"reminiscent of the health and fitness boom eight or nine
years ago," he says, proclaiming, "It's fortuitous that we
have a magazine called Mother Earth News."
   And it's fortuitous that "readers" in faraway galaxies
will get it for free: They really can't complain if it
arrives late.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0145
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0145.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   General Media to Buy
   4 Computer Magazines
   From Capital Cities
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CCB
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Bob Guccione's General Media International
Inc. said it will acquire four computer magazines from ABC
Publishing Cos., a subsidiary of Capital Cities/ABC Inc.
   The magazines -- Compute], Compute's Gazette, Compute's
PC, and Compute's Amiga Resource -- will become part of the
Omni magazine division of closely held General Media. The
purchase price wasn't disclosed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Guccione, best known as the founder and publisher of
Penthouse magazine, has expanded his magazine company in
recent years, by acquiring such titles as Four Wheeler, for
auto enthusiasts, and launching Longevity, a health magazine,
last May.
   Kathy Keeton, president of Omni magazine, said Omni
frequently features stories on computers. She said with the
computer magazines, Omni can "realize some synergy" in
advertising sales and editorial matter.
   "Compute] caters to the home market, and the home-office
market is booming with more than 10 million people who work
at home," said Ms. Keeton. "The magazines have a good
future."
   Compute], a monthly with circulation of 211,794, is in
need of "lots and lots of editorial smarting up." The four
magazines are currently published in Greensboro, N.C., but
Ms. Keeton said she didn't know whether they would stay
there.
</TEXT>
