<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Film Script Fetches Record
   $1.75 Million at Auction
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A film script about a private eye who
joins a former football star to solve a murder sold for a
record $1.75 million.
   "The Last Boy Scout" could have fetched $2 million, but
28-year-old screenwriter Shane Black said he preferred to
sign with the David Geffen Co., an independent producer he
worked with previously.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Recently, it's become almost routine to ask $1 million for
prized screenplays. But industry executives said Tuesday's
sale price far exceeded previous highs.
   A bidding war has broken out during the past year for
"spec scripts," screenplays written without having been
commissioned by a producer or studio.
   The boom, fed in part by an expansion push by Twentieth
Century Fox, Walt Disney Co. and Columbia Pictures, ended the
$300,000 benchmark price for top scripts a year ago.
   Some studio executives say script auctioning has become
too costly. "To get $1 million, it used to have to be a
damned good script. Now, you practically pay that for the
idea alone and wind up with a lot of rewrites," said David
Hoberman, head of Disney's Touchstone unit.
   Others like the change. "I don't know of anything that
generates the excitement of the chase after a big script,"
said John Goldwyn, executive vice president of world-wide
production at MGM/UA Communications Co.
   Screenwriters increasingly are auctioning their work as
studios turn away from the development process, in which
writers are paid to write and rewrite ideas discussed in
advance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0130
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0130.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   UST, American
   Brands Report
   Profit Increases
   ----
   By Kathleen Deveny
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   AMB UST
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
</IN>
<LP>
   American Brands Inc. and UST Inc. both reported strong
earnings for the first quarter, bolstered in part by gains
from tobacco operations.
   American Brands' net income rose 13% to $195.4 million, or
$2 a share, from $172.2 million, or $1.80 a share, a year
earlier. Revenue edged down to $3.2 billion from $3.25
billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The consumer products and insurance company said lower
exchange rates for foreign currencies, especially the British
pound, cut revenue by $116 million and net income by $6
million. Earnings were also adversely affected by the absence
of Southland Life, an insurance company sold in March 1989.
   Operating profit from American Brands' core tobacco
business rose 8% to $281 million on record revenue, driven by
strong unit sales and expanding profit overseas. Unit sales
in the U.S. dropped 9%, but price increases helped boost
profit 3%. The company makes such cigarette brands as
Carlton, Lucky Strike and Pall Mall.
   The company, based in Old Greenwich, Conn., said interest
expense dropped 31%, as strong cash flow allowed the company
to reduce borrowing.
   American Brands' U.S. tobacco volume was weaker than the
industry trend, said Marc Cohen, an analyst with Sanford C.
Bernstein &amp; Co., but the company as a whole had an
above-average quarter.
   At UST, the U.S.'s leading marketer of moist, smokeless
tobacco, earnings jumped 20% to $52.6 million, or 46 cents a
share, from $44 million, or 38 cents a share, a year earlier.
Sales grew 11% to $175.3 million from $157.6 million.
   Domestic unit volume of the Greenwich, Conn., company's
smokeless tobacco products, including the Copenhagen and
Skoal brands, rose 6.6%. "That's definitely above the
industry trend," said Rebecca Barfield, an analyst with First
Boston Corp.
   UST's earnings included a pretax gain of $3 million, or
two cents a share, from the early termination of a licensing
accord for the distribution of pipe tobacco.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
American Brands closed at $64.75, off $1.50, and UST closed
at $26.875, down $1.125.
</TEXT>
