<HL>
   U.K. Public Sector Borrowing
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7C
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   LONDON -- The public sector borrowing requirement, the
most widely used measure of Britain's government deficit or
surplus, showed a deficit of #1.63 billion ($2.67 billion) in
March compared with a surplus of #1.04 billion in February
and a deficit of #2.25 billion in March 1989, the U.K.
Treasury said.
   The March deficit brought the surplus for the year ended
March 31 down to #8 billion, compared with a surplus of #14.5
billion in the previous fiscal year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The government had initially projected a #14 billion
surplus for the latest year, but scaled this forecast back to
#7 billion in March.
