<HL>
   EC Commission Is Critical
   Of U.S. Trade Practices
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9B
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- The European Community Commission, determined
to refute U.S. charges that it is creating a "Fortress
Europe," accused the U.S. of maintaining numerous barriers to
European exports.
   In its annual review of "U.S. trade barriers and unfair
trade practices," the EC listed more than 50 impediments to
trade. Among the sectors singled out by Brussels were public
procurement and banking.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The EC report has been expanded considerably from last
year and includes a wide range of trade practices running
from high U.S. tariffs on footwear to U.S. agricultural
export subsidies. More than a dozen items have been added
since the 1989 report, although commission officials said
only some of these were actually new practices introduced in
the past year.
   They said the longer list reflected the more thorough job
done by EC experts in identifying U.S. trade barriers.
   "We detect a tendency in the U.S. to think that in the
trade game, other countries play unfair while only the U.S.
plays fair . . . this simply isn't true," a commission trade
official said.
   He said the EC report was a response to the U.S. trade
representative's annual report on barriers to foreign trade,
which repeatedly has included EC trade practices. U.S.
officials had no immediate response to the EC document.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0116
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0116.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   West German Metal Workers
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<LP>
   BONN -- The big IG Metall metal workers union rejected an
offer by the employers federation to discuss a further
shortening of the workweek to 35 hours once the competitive
situation in the European Community will allow it.
   The union, which is calling for a cut in the workweek and
a 9% pay increase, said the employers' offer, which also
included some concessions regarding weekend work, represented
"cosmetic changes to a hopelessly obsolete model."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The union's rejection of the employers' new opening
underlined the lack of progress in the difficult 1990 wage
negotiations. IG Metall, which represents more than 2.6
million workers in important sectors of the West German
industry, has said it will stage warning strikes at certain
companies in early May.
   The employers federation said it wanted to set "objective
criteria" that would determine extent and timing of a cut in
working hours after 1993. Union officials said such criteria
would mean indefinite postponement of the shorter workweek.
</TEXT>
