<HL>
   Thursday's Markets:
   Late Sales
   Push Stocks
   Down 20.94
   ---
   Bonds Continue Fall
   But at Slower Pace;
   Dollar Finishes Mixed
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Late-afternoon sell programs knocked the wind out an
already weak stock market, and bond prices continued their
decline, albeit at a slower pace.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost 20.94 points to
close at 2711.94 in moderate trading. Long-term bond prices
were off moderately, while the dollar was mixed, rising
against the mark but falling against the yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts said stock prices remain at the mercy of the
declining bond market. As bond prices fall, interest rates
rise, providing an incentive for investors to seek safety in
cash rather than in stocks or bonds. Once bond prices appear
stabilized, the higher rates that many analysts expect are
likely to attract more investors to bonds than to stocks.
   The erosion of bond prices stems from growing concern that
inflation isn't under control and that the Federal Reserve
will have to drive short-term interest rates higher if it
expects to curb rising prices. Compounding the inflation
worries are apparent selling by Japanese investors and the
prospect early next month of a $30 billion Treasury refunding
auction.
   Bond traders said that with little economic news to drive
the market yesterday, selling pressures moderated
considerably. On Wednesday, long-term Treasury bonds plunged
more than a full point, or more than $10 for each $1,000 of
face amount. Nevertheless, traders are bracing for yields on
long-term Treasury bonds to hit the 9% level in coming weeks.
Yesterday the yield on the Treasury's benchmark 30-year issue
stood at 8.84%.
   Stock prices were moderately weak all of yesterday,
generally tracking bond prices. But computer-assisted sell
programs tied to stock-index arbitrage forced prices even
lower in the final half-hour of trading. Absent the programs,
traders said, the fall in prices that took the Dow
industrials down nearly 33 points Wednesday seemed to have
moderated.
   So far, the downward pressure on stocks has come from the
bond market and not from corporate earnings, which many
analysts expected to be much worse. While some companies'
profits have indeed been disappointing, there have been some
positive surprises.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices fell in moderate trading. Volume on the New
York Stock Exchange totaled 152.9 million shares. Declining
issues surpassed gainers 968 to 511.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices were modestly lower. The 30-year Treasury lost
about 1/8 point.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar was mixed. In late New York trading, the U.S.
currency was quoted at 1.6784 marks and 157.20 yen, compared
with 1.6722 marks and 158.10 yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0114
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0114.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Japan Employer Group
   To Send Delegation
   To Eastern Europe
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN EUROP FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Amid growing expectations that world trade with
Eastern Europe could expand significantly, Japanese business
and government leaders have been stepping up their research
efforts in the region.
   The Japan Federation of Employers' Associations said it
will send a 20-member research mission to Eastern Europe in
late September to study economic and labor conditions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The organization's goal is to get an idea of what type of
economic cooperation governments and businesses in Eastern
Europe are most eager to receive from Japanese business, and
what lessons Japanese business-labor practices and
administrative practices might offer, a spokesman said. The
mission will travel to Poland, Hungary and Czechoslovakia
from Sept. 23 to Oct. 4, he said.
   Meanwhile, the Soviet Union-East Europe Office of the
Ministry of International Trade and Industry is heading a
similar mission to Poland and Hungary. The mission of
ministry's Economic Investment Environment Research Group is
to study the conditions for private investment opportunities,
such as infrastructure, an official said.
   The 70 Japanese executives and government officials on the
ministry's mission traveled to Poland last week, and were in
Hungary this week, he said, noting that this mission differs
from that of the employers' federation in focus but still
reflects the same principle of gaining a better understanding
of business and economic conditions in Eastern Europe.
   Though results won't be reported until the group returns,
the leader of the ministry's mission in Poland indicated that
the market there is potentially attractive, as the country
has made progress in curbing inflation and stabilizing its
currency.
   But he said the overhaul of the legal structure to support
a market economy and the development of infrastructure must
be followed closely, a Japanese daily reported.
   In addition, various Japanese cabinet members, including
Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama and Health and Welfare
Minister Yuji Tsushima, plan to visit the region separately
this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bahrain's Offshore Banking
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9D
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<LP>
   MANAMA, Bahrain -- The total assets of Bahrain's offshore
banking units, or OBUs, rose 7% to $72.58 billion at the end
of December from $68.12 billion a year earlier, the Bahrain
Monetary Agency said.
   The assets of the island's OBUs have risen gradually from
a low in 1986, when the sector held total assets of $55.68
billion. After expanding rapidly in the late 1970s and early
1980s, Bahrain's offshore banking sector was hurt by the
effects on regional economies of the sharp drop in oil prices
during the mid-1980s.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Of the December 1989 assets, $29.96 billion, or 41%, were
held in Arab countries last December, and $14.27 billion, or
20%, were held in Western Europe. Only $7.87 billion, or 11%,
were held in North America.
   On the funding side, $45 billion in liabilities, or 62% of
the total, were held in Arab countries. The banks had
liabilities of $12.72 billion, or 18%, with Western Europe,
and $5.75 billion, or 8%, with North America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
