<HL>
   Strike-Battered Dog
   Riding Hard Road
   With Low Octane
   ---
   Greyhound Woes Continue;
   Easter Travel Down 56%
   From Year-Ago Level
   ----
   By Robert Tomsho
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7E
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
MASS TRANSIT, BUS LINES, SUBWAYS, HIGHWAYS (TRA)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- After a disappointing Easter travel weekend,
debt-laden Greyhound Lines Inc. continues its struggle to
expand its service network and attract enough riders to shore
up its strike-battered balance sheet.
   Just before Easter, the unit of GLI Holding Co. added
several hundred new replacement drivers, restored service to
286 locations and offered customers in some cities free
tickets if their buses arrived late. But with violence
continuing to flare up in the strike by 9,300 members of the
Amalgamated Transit Union, Greyhound only attracted about 44%
the number of riders it did for Easter weekend a year ago.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "I feel that our ridership is very high," said Greyhound
spokeswoman Elizabeth Hale, who said ridership had been
hovering between 50% and 60% of pre-strike levels in the days
immediately preceding the holiday. She attributed the lower
percentage over the Easter weekend itself mainly to the fact
that in 1989, Easter coincided with spring break for many
college students.
   But analysts who follow the closely held company's
publicly traded bonds say Greyhound has yet to maintain the
levels of ridership and revenue that it needs to break even.
"The company has said they need to be at about 70%-plus level
to break even," said Charles Mancuso, senior analyst for
Moody's Investors Service Inc. "The question becomes how long
can they go if they don't achieve that level."
   In a recent Securities and Exchange Commission filing,
Greyhound acknowledged that a prolonged strike could
seriously impair its financial future. Since the strike began
March 2, the company has continued to restore scheduled
service and add replacement drivers in the face of strike
violence.
   The company said that, as of last Tuesday, it was running
about 72% of its prestrike schedules with 2,903 drivers --
2,393 of them new hires.
   But even if the company succeeds in spite of the strike,
some analysts say they are concerned about the long-term
impact of negative publicity surrounding the recent violence,
the additional debt taken on because of the strike and the
problems in rejuvenating Greyhound's charter and package
express businesses, both badly battered by the walkout.
   "They seem to be winning the strike," says Leigh Walzer,
an analyst with R.D. Smith and Co. "The question now is how
strong will the company be going forward."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0103
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0103.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Short Interest
   On Big Board
   Is About Flat
   ---
   But Amex Posts 6.2% Rise
   In Total to Record High
   In the Month to April 12
   ----
   By Robert Daniels
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
SHORT SALES AND SHORT INTEREST (SHO)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Short interest for the month ended April 12
was about flat on the New York Stock Exchange and rose 6.2%
to a record on the American Stock Exchange.
   On the Big Board, Chemical Banking Corp.'s short volume,
which had been inflated by an arbitrage play, plunged as
short sellers covered their positions. The Indianapolis
pharmaceutical concern Eli Lilly &amp; Co. posted the biggest
increase in short volume.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The New York exchange reported that short interest inched
down to 613,933,904 shares at mid-April from 614,559,232
shares at mid-March. On the Amex, short volume rose to
70,931,396 shares from an adjusted 66,776,615 a month
earlier.
   For the year-earlier month, Big Board short volume was
556,831,364 shares, a year-to-year rise of 10.2%. A year ago,
the Amex reported 43,663,617 shares, indicating a 62% climb.
   Traders who sell short borrow stock and sell it, betting
that the stock's price will decline and that they can buy the
shares back later at a lower price for return to the lender.
   Short interest is the number of shares that haven't yet
been purchased for return to lenders. Although a substantial
short position reflects heavy speculation that a stock's
price will decline, some investors consider an increase in
short interest bullish because the borrowed shares eventually
must be bought back.
   Fluctuation in short interest of certain stocks also may
be caused partly by arbitraging. The figures occasionally
include incomplete transactions in restricted stock.
   The level of negative sentiment measured by the Big Board
short interest ratio rose to 4.19 from last month's 3.94. The
ratio is the number of trading days at the exchange's average
daily trading volume that would be required to convert the
total short interest position.
   Some analysts suggest, however, that the ratio has
weakened in value as an indicator because options and other
products can be used to hedge short positions.
   Short volume for the New York parent of Chemical Bank sank
to 2,359,516 shares from 17,257,721 shares. Arbitragers had
been selling Chemical's shares short and then covering their
positions with shares bought at a discount under the
company's dividend-reinvestment plan. Chemical later
tightened the rules of the plan.
   Eli Lilly's short volume grew to 10,270,405 shares from
7,917,352. Uncovered short sales for the bellwether issue
International Business Machines Corp. rose 3.8% to 4,053,955
shares from 3,903,455. Exxon Corp.'s short volume slipped
5.5% to 5,581,248 shares from 5,912,126.
   Leading the Amex short volumes, as it has for some time,
was Texas Air Corp. The airline holding company's short
volume dropped 7.2% to 8,817,325 shares from 9,506,412.
   The adjacent tables show the Big Board and Amex issues in
which a short interest position of at least 100,000 shares
existed as of mid-April or in which the short position had
changed by at least 50,000 shares since mid-March (see tables
-- WSJ April 20, 1990).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
