<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0067
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0067.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Greenspan Says Banks Have Tightened
   Lending but Sees No Credit Crunch Now
   ----
   By David Wessel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
banks in New England and other regions have tightened their
lending standards but it's too soon to say that a credit
crunch is choking the economy.
   In written answers to questions posed by the Senate
Banking Committee, Mr. Greenspan said the Fed believes banks
are reacting to changing economic conditions, bad loans and
"ongoing scrutiny by regulators."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Such tightening could reduce the amount of credit
provided to businesses and consumers . . . with potential
effects on the level of local economic activity," Mr.
Greenspan said. But responding to a query about Massachusetts
from Sen. John Kerry (D., Mass.), the Fed chairman said a
credit crunch "would most likely need to be prolonged and
more severe than we have been able to detect" before it
threatens the economic stability of New England.
   Mr. Greenspan, who said the Fed seeks a prudent balance
between too much restraint on the part of bankers and too
little, noted that bank lending essentially didn't grow at
all in December and January. In February, it grew at an
annual rate of 5.3%. For all of 1989, he noted, bank lending
rose 7.6%. Loan growth in the Northeast and Southwest has
been weaker than the national average. That can reflect
bankers' reluctance to lend or customers' reluctance to
borrow in an uncertain economy or both.
   Mr. Greenspan added that the large losses reported by
thrifts throughout the 1980s and, more recently, by
commercial banks "suggests that financing activity in the
real estate industry, in particular, has been excessive."
   Mr. Greenspan disclosed new Fed data showing that the 50
largest bank-holding companies at the end of last year had
$125.5 billion in loans outstanding to highly leveraged
transactions, a 50% increase from the end of 1988. So far,
those loans, which include bank lending for debt-financed
takeovers, are performing better than other kinds of loans,
the Fed data show. But the proportion of loans for highly
leveraged transactions that are going sour is on the rise.
   The Fed currently is conducting special examinations of
certain banks with high concentrations of such loans "to
determine if significant deterioration is taking place," the
Fed chairman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0066
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0066.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Commodities:
   World Oil Prices Surge After OPEC Schedules
   An Emergency Meeting of Ministers for May 2
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
COMMODITY MARKETS FOR METALS (MIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   World oil prices surged after OPEC used a pricing tactic
that has served it well in the past -- the scheduling of a
meeting of the oil ministers.
   North Sea crudes spurted as much as 90 cents a barrel in
European spot markets, and one U.S. crude-futures contract
increased even more, after Sadek Boussena, Algeria's oil
minister and acting president of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, set May 2 as the date for
beginning an emergency meeting in Geneva of the market
monitoring committee.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Although that policy-setting committee has only eight
ministers, Mr. Boussena invited all 13 of OPEC's oil
ministers to attend the meeting, indicating that it could be
turned into a full OPEC conference. He then postponed to June
25 the regular midyear conference, which previously had been
scheduled to start May 25.
   The May 2 meeting "will examine the measures needed to
halt the constant degradation of the market and to raise
prices so as to re-establish them at the level set by OPEC,"
Mr. Boussena said.
   The announcement sparked heavy trading in most of the
world's oil markets, with prices immediately beginning to
rise. Accelerating the rally were traders who had bet on
further price declines and had to quickly buy contracts to
cover their positions.
   "There was a lot of `short' covering; gasoline was very
strong, but the real interest was in crude," said Eric
Bolling, an energy futures trader in New York with Edge
Trading Corp.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, unleaded gasoline for
May delivery spiraled up 2.23 cents a gallon to settle at
61.78 cents, while the June motor fuel contract jumped the
limit of two cents a gallon. Heating oil futures also were
up, with June and later months showing the bigger gains.
   But the star in futures trading was West Texas
Intermediate crude for May delivery. Analysts said it went up
faster because more traders had bet against it in recent
weeks as prices plummeted. Also, today is the May contract's
last trading day; that may have contributed to the
volatility.
   Whatever the reason, May WTI gained $1.10 a barrel to
settle at $18.06. The June crude contract was up 78 cents to
$18.87.
   Although analysts and traders generally attributed most of
the day's price run-ups to the OPEC announcements, few were
prepared to predict whether previously depressed oil markets
had indeed turned around. "I won't say prices have bottomed,"
said Mr. Bolling, "but they should be trading higher" in the
days ahead.
   In other commodity markets yesterday:
                                                                                                       

   COPPER: Futures prices continued their recent pattern of
moving over a narrow range. The May contract ended with a
gain of 0.40 cent a pound at $1.1660. Nearterm tightness of
supplies is reflected in the premiums being enjoyed by
soonest-to-expire positions in both London and New York over
more deferred contracts. That, plus the continuing Peruvian
miners and smelter workers strike, now in the sixth week,
remain the principal underlying price-supporting factors, one
analyst noted. However, according to William O'Neill, vice
president for research for Elders Futures Inc., New York,
some progress may be taking place in the Peruvian labor
situation. Union leaders representing the workers of Southern
Peru Copper Corp., who walked off March 12, have scheduled a
meeting with company officials, he said. Also, Mr. O'Neill
said, workers who went on strike at the same time at a
separately owned mine, Tintaya, have returned to work.
"Although no agreement has been reached, it has been reported
that union leaders have received an offer they're willing to
accept," he said. While improvement is possible in the
Peruvian situation, he said, it is still unsolved and is
offsetting some of the concern over recent economic
statistics that indicate a slowing economy, particularly
weaker auto sales and poorer employment statistics. The
automobile industry is a major copper-user. Traders who
follow charts also appear to be more cautious, Mr. O'Neill
noted, since there appears to be resistance around the
$1.20-a-pound level for the May contract "and definitely
major resistance at around $1.25."
                                                                                                       

   GRAINS and SOYBEANS: Prices of corn, wheat and soybean
futures contracts rallied late in the trading session
yesterday amid continuing rumors about the Soviet Union's
interest in making major purchases. At the Chicago Board of
Trade, wheat prices were also supported by concerns about
tight supplies of soft red winter wheat. Supplies of the
crop, which is grown in the Midwest, usually reach their
tightest levels in the spring before the new wheat crops
begin to be harvested. As a result, concerns about a squeeze
on wheat supplies are traditional in April. Despite the
rally, the prospects for the wheat crop in the U.S. continue
to improve, according to Katharina Zimmer, an analyst at
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., New York. Fields in the Southern Plains,
where the hard red winter wheat crop is grown, are generally
in their best condition since the 1988 drought began. Some
dry regions of the Pacific Northwest are expected to get
moisture this week.
                                                                                                       

   LIVESTOCK and MEATS: Prices of hog futures contracts rose
amid reports that the slaughter continues to lag behind
normal levels because of tight supplies of fattened hogs. The
low slaughter is causing strong prices of hogs during a time
of the year when prices are usually their weakest. After the
close of trading today, the Agriculture Department is slated
to release its quarterly survey of feedlots in 13 major ranch
states. Thomas Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp.,
Arlington Heights, Ill., said he expects the department to
report that the number of cattle on feedlots in those states
rose 1% on April 1 from the same 1989 date. That would be the
largest number in feedlots, which fatten cattle for
slaughter, during an April 1 survey since 1978. Traders
expect the report to indicate that the cattle slaughter
during the second quarter will be heavy.
                                                                                                       

   SUGAR: Futures prices fell back from Wednesday's gains on
a denial by the Soviet Union that it had bought sugar in the
free market. The July contract ended with a loss of 0.26 cent
a pound at 15.30 cents. This decline erased slightly more
than half of the 0.48 cent gain posted Wednesday. Arthur
Stevenson, analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., New
York, said that an official of Sakhar, the Soviet sugar
trading corporation, stated that the Soviet Union hadn't
bought sugar on the world market. "While that is the answer
one would expect, because they aren't going to reveal such
information," Mr. Stevenson said, "I tend to believe them
this time." Apparently, most traders also thought that way,
because many decided to take profits, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Continues Slide on Earnings;
   Seagate Technology Down About 20%
   ----
   By Anne Newman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter investors continued to punish stocks of
companies with disappointing earnings, sending Seagate
Technology down about 20% in active trading after the
computer disk drive maker reported third-quarter profit below
analysts' expectations.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index closed off 2.52 at 429.00, a
0.58% drop, on 145.6 million shares, down from 149.7 million.
By comparison, the Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped
0.77%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Declining stocks continued to outpace advancers, 1,065 to
820, while 127 stocks hit new lows compared with 83 reaching
new highs.
   "It seems this market is taking earnings disappointments a
lot more strongly than positives," said Peter Coolidge,
senior OTC trader at Kidder Peabody. "If earnings come out
and are in line or a little worse then expected, stocks take
it on the chin. But if they come out a little better than
expected, they don't go up as much."
   Seagate fell 3 1/8 to close at 12 1/8. Apple Computer also
dropped, down 3 at 40 1/4 on 4.3 million shares. The company
told analysts in a conference call late Wednesday that it
expects revenue for the second half of the year to grow only
7% to 10% from a year earlier, rather than 15% or more as
previously estimated, according to Goldman Sachs analyst
Daniel Benton.
   Mr. Benton said he reduced his investment opinion on the
computer manufacturer to a "hold" from a "trading buy"
because of the expected softness. Slower growth should show
up particularly in sales of Apple's less expensive computers,
such as the Macintosh Portable, Mr. Benton said.
   Among gainers was Lotus Development, up 1 to 34 1/4 after
reporting first-quarter earnings on the high end of Wall
Street expectations. The Cambridge, Mass., software maker
attributed the earnings strength to across-the-board customer
demand and accelerated international sales.
   However, technology stocks generally were weaker, noted
Lawrence Rice, manager of OTC trading for Los Angeles-based
Wedbush Morgan Securities. Like Mr. Coolidge of Kidder
Peabody, Mr. Rice said he saw both buying and selling
interest scattered across a number of sectors.
   Among the market's cheerleaders was Mitch Meisler, OTC
director of marketing for Shearson Lehman Hutton, who said he
expects the bond market to "turn on a dime any day now" with
the OTC market following. Mr. Meisler added that he believes
fears of inflation are overblown.
   Among the day's top leaders were two preferred shares of
First Executive Corp., the Los Angeles holder of a large
portfolio of junk bonds. First Executive cumulative preferred
series F jumped 1 5/8 at 8 3/4, while the series E preferred
shares rose 1 3/8 to 5 7/8. Craig Mosovitz, trader at
Interstate/Johnson Lane Securities, said he saw demand for
the preferred issues from investors who were paid their
dividends this week and expect future payments.
   However, Thomas Rosencrants, director of research for the
brokerage's Atlanta office, cautioned that First Executive's
most recent quarterly report indicates it has sufficient
funds to meet its fixed obligations only through 1990, but
will require additional funds for the first quarter of 1991.
Mr. Rosencrants said he's advising investors to avoid First
Executive's preferred and common shares.
   DeKalb Genetics, a commercial seed producer, gained 1 1/2
to 37 3/4 after announcing it had successfully inserted
foreign genes into corn plants. Also gaining was BioTechnica
International, up 3/8 at 4 1/2, which made a similar
bioengineering claim in January.
   Shares of Eastchester Financial, White Plains, N.Y., hit a
new 52-week high at 16 1/4, up 1 1/2, on more than 13 times
average volume after announcing it reached an agreement to be
acquired for $20 a share by North Fork Bancorp, based in
Mattituck, N.Y. Up in sympathy was another New York bank,
Peoples Westchester Savings, which rose 1/4 at 16 1/4.
   Shares of Chemfix Technologies, which treats hazardous
waste, rose 5/8 to 6 3/8 in heavy trading after an analyst at
Rotan Mosle recommended purchase of the stock, according to
Dow Jones Professional Investor Report. Also, Ohio Casualty
converted its preferred stake into 315,000 shares of Chemfix
common stock, which it then sold, according to the news
service.
   Shares of SciMed Life Systems, a maker of catheters used
in heart surgery, fell 7/8 to 25 7/8 on 1.45 million shares
after a competitor, C. R. Bard, said it sent a letter to
SciMed alleging the company is infringing on a Bard patent,
the investor report said. However, Bard hasn't yet filed a
lawsuit suit alleging patent infringement.
   Mr. Coolidge of Kidder Peabody said profit taking
apparently pressured shares of two companies involved in
cleaning up the environment. Sevenson Environmental Services
fell 2 to 12 3/4 and ERC Environmental &amp; Energy Services lost
3/4 to 11 1/4. Mr. Coolidge noted that "the hype" about the
forthcoming Earth Day had inflated the shares of some
environmental services companies.
   ---
   Craig S. Smith contributed to this column.
</TEXT>
