<HL>
   Merchants National
   Finds Artful Way
   To Settle a Bad Debt
   ---
   Chief to Personally Pay Back
   $1.5 Million Loan Granted
   To an Art-Dealer Friend
   ----
   By Scott Kilman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B18A
</SO>
<CO>
   MCHN
</CO>
<LP>
   The executive who has suffered through the most
embarrassing annual meeting so far this year is probably Otto
N. Frenzel, chairman and chief executive of Merchants
National Corp.
   The bank holding company disclosed during its meeting
Tuesday that the 59-year-old Indianapolis executive has
agreed to personally pay off about $1.5 million in defaulted
loans that a bank unit made in 1988 to a friend, art dealer
Peg L. Goldberg.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ms. Goldberg, who had been introduced to the lending
officers by Mr. Frenzel, used the loan to buy four
sixth-century Byzantine mosaics that turned out to have been
taken from the ceiling of a church in North Cyprus.
   A few months after the bank lent the money, Mr. Frenzel
became an investor in the project to resell the mosaics --
portraits of Jesus and the apostles Matthew and James.
   Ms. Goldberg tried to sell the mosaics to the J. Paul
Getty Museum for $20 million. But the mosaics sparked a
landmark case on whether foreign governments can recover
stolen art in a U.S. court. In September, a federal district
judge ruled that the mosaics should be returned to the Greek
Orthodox Church.
   Ms. Goldberg appealed the decision. But she can't sell the
mosaics so she doesn't have the means to pay off the debt.
   Mr. Frenzel, who couldn't be reached for comment, was
cleared by an internal investigation of any wrongdoing. But
he decided to pay off the loan because "it did cause some
embarrassment for the corporation as it was handled by the
news media," a spokesman said.
   Mr. Frenzel, whose annual base salary was listed in the
proxy as $379,300, didn't mention the mosaics during his
speech to shareholders. However, James D. Massey, president,
announced the agreement.
   Mr. Frenzel "wants to put this to rest," the spokesman
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0062
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0062.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Moody's Weighs
   Downgrading
   Citicorp Debt
   ---
   Long, Short Terms Studied;
   Move Could Shake Up
   Nation's Bank System
   ----
   By Robert Guenther
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   CCI
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- In a move that could shake the nation's
banking system, Moody's Investors Service Inc. placed the
long-term and, for the first time, the short-term debt of
Citicorp and some units under review for a possible
downgrade.
   A downgrading would affect $31 billion of the parent
company's securities, increasing the company's short-term
cost of funds and dealing a major blow to its prestige.
Importantly, the short-term rating of Citibank, its flagship,
isn't under review.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Citicorp always has been the bank that was `too big to
downgrade.' They were regarded as untouchable," said Ann
Robinson, a bond analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette
Securities Corp. "If Citicorp is downgraded, it's like saying
that the whole U.S. banking system is being downgraded."
   With $230 billion in assets, Citicorp is the nation's
largest banking company and a bellwether for the banking
industry. Analysts say a downgrading of Citicorp could
intensify investor jitters about banks as a group and cause
them to demand higher yields on bank debt.
   The bond market has treated Citicorp debt, whose senior
debt carries an singleA-1 rating, much more kindly than most
other bank debt. There has been plenty of demand for its
debt, and prices have held up comparatively well at a time
when yields on some bank debt, such as Midlantic Corp., have
climbed to 20%.
   Moody's announcement came after the close of trading. In
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange yesterday,
Citicorp common stock fell 21.5 cents to close at $23.75 a
share.
   While ratings reviews don't always result in ratings
changes, some analysts believe that, in the current harsh
regulatory climate for banks, a downgrading of Citicorp is
likely. Moody's, which has been aggressive in downgrading
bank ratings, recently placed obligations of Chase Manhattan
Corp., which has a more conservative risk profile and a
stronger capital base, under review for an upgrade. But
instead of upgrading Chase, it affirmed its existing rating.
   Christopher T. Mahoney, a vice president at Moody's, said
the company was concerned by Citicorp's mounting levels of
nonperforming loans in commercial real estate, highly
leveraged transactions and developing-country loans, as well
as its capital adequacy.
   "We have to take a look in greater depth at their
exposure," said Mr. Mahoney.
   In response, a Citicorp spokesman said, "We trust that
Moody's will agree with us that a change isn't justified."
   Moody's, a unit of Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp., last reviewed
Citicorp's rating about two years ago at the height of
concern about developing country-loans. At that time, Moody's
affirmed the holding company's debt rating but downgraded the
bank.
   Citicorp satisfies about 15% of its funding needs through
the commercial paper market and about 10% by issuing longterm
debt. About 60% of its funds come from customer deposits,
which wouldn't be affected by a rating change.
   Citicorp is the biggest lender to commercial real estate,
with a $13 billion portfolio of loans outstanding. The
company is also the biggest lender to highly leveraged
transactions, with $7.9 billion outstanding; and to
developing countries, with $8.6 billion in medium- and
long-term debt.
   In the first quarter, Citicorp's nonperforming assets
climbed 11% from a year earlier to $8.1 billion, while its
reserves to absorb losses have remained about 61%, below the
70% level kept by some other banks. And its common equity, at
3.6% of total assets, is well below the 4% or more of most
peer banks.
   Citicorp has pointed to the global and varied nature of
its business, particularly its strong consumer business, in
arguing why its numbers don't always coincide with industry
norms. And Chairman John S. Reed has adamantly insisted that
he wants to build Citicorp's capital base to 4.5% through
retained earnings and nonstrategic asset sales and not by
issuing new shares, which would dilute existing shareholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0061
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0061.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   How Poll Was Conducted
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   DJ GE
</CO>
<LP>
   The Wall Street Journal/NBC News poll was based on
nationwide telephone interviews of 1,001 registered voters
conducted April 11, 12, 14 and 16 by the polling
organizations of Peter Hart and Robert Teeter.
   The sample was drawn from 260 randomly selected geographic
points in the continental U.S. Each region was represented in
proportion to its population. Households were picked by a
method that gave all phone numbers, listed and unlisted, an
equal chance of being included. One registered voter, 18 or
older, was selected from each household by a procedure to
provide the correct number of male and female respondents.
The results of the survey were minimally weighted by income
and race to assure that the poll accurately reflects
registered voters nationwide.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Chances are 19 of 20 that if all registered voters in the
U.S. had been surveyed using the same questionnaire, the
findings would differ from these poll results by no more than
3.2 percentage points in either direction. The margin of
error for subgroups would be larger.
   (See: "Friends of the Earth: Americans Are Willing to
Sacrifice to Reduce Pollution, They Say --- High
Environmental Concern Lifts Support for Recycling, Car Pools,
Cloth Diapers --- But Job Losses Give Pause" -- WSJ April 20,
1990)
</TEXT>
