<HL>
   Law:
   Canada Will Appeal
   Antitrust Panel Ruling
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- The Canadian government decided to appeal a
Quebec Superior Court ruling that the Competition Tribunal,
which reviews antitrust cases, is unconstitutional.
   The appeal is to be heard by the Quebec Court of Appeal.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The tribunal, which was established four years ago,
reviews cases referred to it by the government's antitrust
agency, the Bureau of Competition Policy.
   The tribunal's powers were challenged by Quebec City-based
Alex Couture Inc., a processor of animal waste products,
after the company was blocked from taking control of a
competitor.
   The Superior Court ruled that the tribunal, with members
including judges, economists and business specialists, had
powers that violate constitutional guarantees of fair and
impartial judicial proceedings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0058
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0058.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Money-Fund Assets
   Declined $1.25 Billion
   In the Latest Week
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Assets of the nation's 508 money-market funds
fell $1.25 billion, to $388.60 billion, in the week ended
Wednesday, according to the Investment Company Institute, a
Washington-based trade association.
   "With short-term interest rates continuing to hold fairly
steady, the overall change in money-market fund assets held
in individual accounts was small," said Jacob Dreyer, vice
president and chief economist at the institute. "Massive
flows of individual tax payments and refunds, typical for
mid-April, also had no discernible effect on money-market
fund assets. On the other hand, money-market fund assets held
in institutional accounts dropped over $1 billion, most
probably in response to an abrupt rise in the federal funds
rate."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Assets of 246 general-purpose funds fell $467.3 million,
to $133.05 billion, while assets of 102 broker-dealer funds
rose $237.3 million, to $165.32 billion. Assets of 160
institutional funds fell $1.02 billion, to $90.23 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900420-0057
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900420-0057.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Knight-Ridder Says
   Profit Climbed 26%
   In the First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
04/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   KRI
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   MIAMI -- Knight-Ridder Inc. reported that first-quarter
net income climbed 26% to $25.8 million from $20.5 million a
year ago, due in part to lower newsprint and interest costs.
   The giant media concern said per-share profit rose 28% in
the latest quarter to 50 cents from 39 cents, based on 51.8
million shares outstanding in the latest quarter compared
with 52.6 million a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder said revenue rose 2.6% to $554.7 million
from $540.7 million a year earlier.
   The company said reduced losses in its Detroit newspaper
operations and good performance in its Business Information
Services Division, particularly its MoneyCenter and Dialog
products, contributed to the improved results.
   It said interest costs in the quarter fell to $14.1
million from $23 million a year earlier, as a result of the
pay-down of debt with funds from the 1989 sale of eight
television stations and its Pasadena newspaper.
   In a statement, Robert F. Singleton, senior vice president
and chief financial officer, said, "Looking ahead,
Knight-Ridder is well positioned to continue to absorb a soft
advertising environment and should produce among the best
earnings-per-share gains in our industry this year." He added
that "barring some unforeseen financial setback, 1990 will be
Knight-Ridder's 15th consecutive year of growth in earnings
per share from continuing operations."
</TEXT>
